The before really didnt look any different except there was a lot more fat in the \<style> 
blocks, and they weren't responsive. 

As for what exactly is going on here, lets start with the second div child of article,
holding the a>image. ```'row-xs center-xs'``` is telling the div that 
from 0 - the xs breakpoint, we're a row with centered content. ```'col-sm-4 end-sm'``` tells it
that from xs-sm or above, we're a column with width 4/12 and are to be rendered at the end of the row.

For the first div, ```'"last-xs row-xs first-sm col-sm-8"'``` means that from 0-xs, we're 
a row and we're rendered last, so at the bottom, and from sm -> inf , were a column with a width
of 8/12 and we're rendered first, so on the left. 

".previewholder" is a class that just constrains the image to the div its in, and limitoverflow 
limits the contents to 2 lines. The most important bits of the css are below.

